The problem is that your test cases being so similar to your validators make it easy to come up with such hacky solutions.

A desperate coder might produce this hacky code to get 100% on test cases, and unfortunately due to your validators being so similar, they would also get 100% after submitting:
s = len(input())
if s < 7:print(1)
elif s < 20:print(7)
else:print(88)

On a Reverse mode clash, this is particularly bad, because there's no way for them to know that such a solution is bad. If it works for all test cases, then who is to say that their solution is not the correct one? This is why it's best to add more test cases for Reverse clashes, to make sure that the only reasonable solution that works is the correct one.
